<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911202-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>911202-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Nevada Power Co.:   EPA Levies $400,000 Fine   For Pollution-Gear Bypass</HL><DATE>12/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   NVP</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)WESTERN U.S. ELECTRIC UTILITIES (UEW)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><GV>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEVADA (NV)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Nevada Power Co. will pay $400,000 to settle charges thatit violated federal Clean Air Act laws at its Reid-GardnerGenerating Station near Moapa, Nev., the EnvironmentalProtection Agency said.   Officials at the Las Vegas-based utility couldn't bereached for comment.</LP><TEXT>   The agency charged that Nevada Power bypassedmalfunctioning pollution-control devices instead of shuttingdown or reducing operations at its facility. The utility alsowas charged with failing to properly file required excessemissions reports.   Nevada Power's actions resulted in the excess emission ofsulfur dioxide and particulate pollutants into theatmosphere, the agency said. High exposure to sulfur dioxidecauses breathing difficulties and aggravates respiratory andcardiovascular disease.</TEXT></DOC>